<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Robaina Addresses Integration Association </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Robaina Addresses Integration Association </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0804005094 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 2148 GMT 6 Apr 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA0804005094 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Montevideo, 6 Apr (PL) -- Speaking here today, Cuban 
Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina called for a more humane 
approach to Latin American integration "because its sole purpose 
is the well-being of our peoples." 
  The minister spoke at the Latin American Integration 
Association (ALADI) headquarters. He called on association 
members to work for the convergence of subregional processes and 
for joint action on economic, social, and political issues. He 
referred to the need to accomplish more in this sense by 
gradually integrating production and service sectors. 
  In regard to the island's situation, Robaina asserted that 
his government is taking concrete steps to restore as quickly as 
possible the principal economic indicators. 
  Robaina added that in his country everything is subject to 
debate at several levels so as to resolve current problems. 
  He also denounced the economic, commercial, and financial 
blockade imposed by the United States for the past 30 years and 
said the measure was a flagrant, massive, and systematic 
violation of human rights. 
  The minister added that the Caribbean country will not 
negotiate over its sovereignty or its right to speak for itself. 
Nor will it abandon the social achievements it has accomplished. 
  The head of Cuban diplomacy arrived in Uruguay last Monday 
for an official three-day visit which will continue until 
tomorrow, 7 April, according to reports. 
  During his stay, Robaina was received by President Luis 
Alberto Lacalle and met with cabinet members, including his 
colleague Sergio Abreu, businessmen, intellectuals, and 
compatriots who reside in that country. 
  Robaina's South American tour includes Ecuador, Peru, 
Argentina, and Paraguay, according to sources in the Caribbean 
delegation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

