<F P=106> [From the "Early Morning" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The meeting of Inter-American Development Bank [IDB] 
governors has begun in Guadalajara. They talked about economic 
growth and the fight against poverty as requirements for 
political stabilization and a more just society. Patricia 
Gutierrez has filed a report: 
  [Begin recording] [Gutierrez] As the 20th century comes to 
an 
end and as we approach the threshold of a new millennium, no 
country is immune to events that shape politics and economics at 
a world level. This is what President Carlos Salinas de Gortari 
said as he opened the IDB governors assembly. 
  [Salinas] As we look forward, we must start facing the 
challenges common to all nations: the head-on fight against 
poverty; a solution to the world dilemma of creating and 
ensuring employment; the construction of a strong and lasting 
democracy; the protection and preservation of our natural and 
cultural resources; and the endless fight against a criminal 
force--drug trafficking. 
  [Gutierrez] Before the 46 IDB governors and hundreds of 
representatives from financial institutions and governments of 
many nations, the Mexican head of state stressed his commitment 
to contributing to the creation of more just societies, more 
efficient economies, and stronger and more democratic 
institutions. 
  Pedro Aspe, finance and public credit secretary who also 
attended the meeting, said there are no deviations from the path 
the country has chosen to follow. He said: We believe 
investors will continue to have a long-term vision to ensure the 
viability and permanence of economic recovery. He maintained 
national unity prevailed during the painful, difficult, and 
unexpected situations Mexico experienced during the first few 
months of the year. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

