<H3> <TI>   Aristide Spokesman Denounces Move </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Aristide Spokesman Denounces Move </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL1204214494 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1030 
GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1204214494 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] The implementation of Article 
149 of the Constitution does not have a future, according to 
Jean-Claude Martineau, spokesman for President Jean-Bertrand 
Aristide. Martineau said this is a return to the Nerette-Bazin 
method. Ever since the September 1991 coup d'etat, the country 
has been led only by General Raoul Cedras and [Lieutenant] 
Colonel Michel Francois, Martineau states: 
  [Begin Martineau recording, in Creole] This is not the first 
time men have tried to establish an unconstitutional government. 
They did it with Nerette and Honorat. Then they did it with 
Bazin. In fact, all these things are maneuvers, but everybody 
knows that the true head of the country is the Army. I (?see) 
those men bustling about; I do not know what they hope to 
achieve. In fact, [words indistinct]. It seems that in their 
minds, this Constitution has been shelved for a long time. So we 
will see -- if they succeed in setting up a government -- 
whether they have more power than Nerette, Honorat, or Bazin 
because we know that only Cedras and Michel Francois are 
governing. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

