<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Police Suggest Colosio Shot With 2 Different Guns </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Police Suggest Colosio Shot With 2 Different Guns </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1204223194 Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1204223194 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=105> Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Early Morning" newscast] </F>
  [Text] In Tijuana, Baja California, Dr. Gustavo Salazar 
Fernandez, the legal medical expert who performed the autopsy on 
Luis Donaldo Colosio, said that the bullets that killed the 
former PRI [Institutional Revolutionary Party] presidential 
candidate were fired from different weapons. Gerardo Segura 
filed this report from Tijuana, Baja California: 
  [Segura] Two people may be implicated in the assassination 
of 
Luis Donaldo Colosio. According to reports disclosed by Federal 
Judicial Police agents present on the day of the murder, the 
bullet fired at the head of the PRI candidate was different from 
the one that hit the abdomen. They stated that the bullet in 
the skull destroyed a large amount of brain because it 
fragmented, contrary to the one in the abdomen, which did not 
seriously damage the internal organs. 
  The informants, who in light of the current events asked to 
remain anonymous, expressed their distrust in the official 
report. Given this situation, Dr. Gustavo Salazar Fernandez, 
legal medical expert, affirmed that the autopsy performed on 
Colosio did not establish whether one or two firearms were used 
for the attack. 
  [Begin Salazar recording] We recover projectiles left inside 
the body, if any, or state if there was fragmentation. It is 
impossible to retrieve them in each and every case. The autopsy 
report does not officially establish the caliber of the 
projectile. This is done by special request of a prosecutor or 
at a given time when the ballistic tests are performed. 
  From a strictly medical viewpoint, we try to be descriptive. 
[end recording] 
  [Segura] Salazar added, however, that it is possible that 
two different guns may have been used by two different 
perpetrators, but the exhumation and new inspections of the body 
would not provide sufficient evidence to confirm or support such 
hypotheses. 
  Informants of the Federal Judicial Police said that the 
second shot may have come from the person who dove at the feet 
of Luis Donaldo Colosio. Authorities are still searching for 
that person. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

