<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Secretary Views Deficit, Economic Recovery </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Finance Secretary Views Deficit, Economic Recovery </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1204034594 Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 
0430 GMT 9 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1204034594 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City XEW Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Beatriz Garcia; from the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] There will be no 1994 fiscal deficit in Mexico 
despite the events in Chiapas and PRI [Institutional 
Revolutionary Party] candidate Luis Donaldo Colosio's 
assassination, said Finance Secretary Pedro Aspe Armella. He 
has said the country's economic recovery began in November 1993. 
  [Begin Aspe recording] The agreement was ratified in 
November. The economy had reached a deadlock in October, and we 
already had a negative 3-percent drop in industrial production. 
Ratification of the agreement took place in November, and 
industrial production rose to 0 percent that month. Recovery 
began in December, and figures for the industrial sector in 
December show a 4.1-percent increase. The change was truly 
dramatic. [end recording] 
  Secretary Aspe has said even though the events in Chiapas 
and 
Mr. Colosio's death were reflected in the financial market, a 
progressive adjustment has occurred, and this has allowed us to 
withstand the situation. He said all the country's sectors 
reasserted their pledge with ratification of the pact for 
stability, competitiveness, and employment to continue with a 
gradual 3-percent economic recovery, a 7-percent inflation rate, 
which is less than last year's inflation, and a zero fiscal 
deficit. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

