<H3> <TI>   President To Announce `Controversial' Decision </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President To Announce `Controversial' Decision </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1304005294 Panama City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 
2300 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1304005294 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City Circuito RPC Television </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "RPC Television News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] President Guillermo Endara has announced that on 18 
April he will disclose a decision he has made, a decision which 
will generate controversy and prompt criticism against him. 
  The president has warned the statements he is planning to 
make on a television network broadcast on 18 April will shock 
the Panamanian community. He has said the mere thought of it 
makes him ill. 
  [Begin Endara recording] The only reason I am ill is due to 
the worry this decision has caused me. This decision is that 
I.... [pauses] I have made a very difficult decision, and it may 
be very controversial. I will speak on a national network on 18 
April at 1900. At that time you will know why I am ill. You 
will have to wait until 18 April to know. [end recording] 
  The president made the announcement during inauguration of a 
bridge that links the so-called old section of the Free Zone 
with the France Field warehouses in Colon Province. [The 
announcement is] prompting speculation of a possible 
resignation, because the president said repeatedly over the past 
few days that his feet are itching to leave the Palace of the 
Herons. 
  [Begin recording] [Endara] In reality it has nothing to do 
with that other foot disease. It has nothing to do with the 
feet. This is a disease of the head and heart. 
  [Unidentified reporter] Is it a political decision, Mr. 
President? 
  [Endara] It is definitely political, but it is my duty. It 
will be very controversial, and I will be widely criticized, but 
it is my duty. [end recording] 
  Despite reporters' persistent questions, Endara declined to 
provide any details regarding the statements he will make on 18 
April at 1900, and he appealed for patience until then. 

</TEXT>

