<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Puts Candidate Samper in Lead </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll Puts Candidate Samper in Lead </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1304044794 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1800 GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1304044794 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Carlos Mario Diaz; from the "NTC News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The two leading presidential candidates' intense 
political activities along the Atlantic coast coincided with a 
survey published by the newspaper EL TIEMPO today showing 
Ernesto Samper received 49 percent of voter support compared 
with 39 percent for Andres Pastrana. This brings Ernesto Samper 
close to the percentage of votes that would determine the 
presidential elections in the first round. 
  [Begin Samper recording] I think the decision to choose Dr. 
Humberto de la Calle was predictable, as the report so clearly 
states. He is a serious, very responsible person, a great 
constitutionalist, and he is well aware of the country's 
problems. He guarantees not only a responsible ticket but also 
the Liberal Party's unity. [end recording] 
  Samper also warned of the risks of being overconfident: 
  [Begin Samper recording] My principal enemy at this moment 
is overconfidence. I ask all those who have supported me, 
especially the Liberals, not to ease up in this campaign. The 
election is not won yet. It is true things are going along very 
well, but we must do better to exceed the 50 percent needed to 
win in the first round. [end recording] 
  Samper and Pastrana concentrated their political activities 
on the Atlantic coast. This area of the country has become a 
decisive factor in the campaign, given its enormous electoral 
potential. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

