<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   General Responds to Dismissal, Rejects Charges </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    General Responds to Dismissal, Rejects Charges </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1304140394 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1304140394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with former General Jesus Armando Arias Cabrales </F>
by Sandra Vergara; place and date not given; from the "Noticiero 
Nacional" program -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Vergara] Do you feel responsible for the civilians 
reported missing or killed in the Justice Palace takeover? 
  [Arias] I do not feel responsible, nor do any of my men. We 
have never felt responsible for the situation. The 
responsibilities we assumed were determined by operational 
directives and dictated by our commanders. Of course some 
people died, but everyone tends to forget or they neglect to 
mention that the public forces' actions allowed us to rescue 
more than 250 hostages. 
  [Vergara] Do you feel like the scapegoat for this whole 
thing? 
  [Arias] Yes, I think so, judging from the results of the 
Attorney General's Office investigation, meaning the resolutions 
issued in 1989 implying that Colonel Edilberto Sanchez and 
General Arias were the only ones at the Justice Palace. This is 
not a matter of blaming someone else. The investigation should 
have been more thorough and decisions should have been based on 
the facts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

