<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> NAFTA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japanese Agency Views Investments in NAFTA </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japanese Agency Views Investments in NAFTA </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1104141394 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 10 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 9--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1104141394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In connection with the implementation of the North 
America Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) last January, the Economic 
Planning Agency [EPA] has conducted a survey on the agreement's 
impact on Japanese companies' investment behavior. According to 
the survey results, Japanese companies are not yet highly 
motivated for investments in Mexico and other NAFTA nations, and 
the EPA concluded that NAFTA's impact on the companies' behavior 
has not clearly been observed so far. 
  As a trilateral agreement among the United States, Canada, 
and Mexico, NAFTA is seeking tariff cuts on a step-by-step basis 
to establish a free trade zone involving the three nations. 
Following the implementation of NAFTA, the EPA surveyed 1,990 
Japanese companies which have sales or production subsidiaries 
overseas. As a result of the January survey, responses were 
obtained from 635 companies. 
  In response to a (multi-choice answer) question asking in 
which countries or regions companies desire to expand their 
operations, 41.6 percent said they want to expand business in 
the United States; however, those who favored Mexico and Canada 
remained at 10.4 and 6.5 percent, respectively. In contrast, 
39.7 percent were interested in Newly Industrialized Economies 
(NIES) in Asia, 53.2 percent preferred ASEAN, and 51.3 percent 
were for China. The companies thus showed great interest in 
Asia rather than NAFTA. Commenting on this, the EPA said that 
the business sector prefers brisk and prospective markets, and 
that NAFTA is unlikely to drastically change companies' 
investment policies for the time being. 
  Yet, about 40 percent of the companies that are planning 
expansion of operations in Mexico said their plans are to "catch 
up with the regional economic merger." The EPA said that 
influence of NAFTA is observed on this point. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-10508 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat071__a94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-071-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cavallo Conditions Patents Law on U.S. Concessions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cavallo Conditions Patents Law on U.S. Concessions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0704191294 Buenos Aires LA NACION in Spanish 7 Apr 94 
Section 1 p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY0704191294 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires LA NACION </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Finance Minister Domingo Cavallo took people by 
surprise by making a categorical remark conditioning the 
approval of the new patents law to a greater opening of the U.S. 
market or to Argentina joining NAFTA. 
  Only four days before crucial elections for the government, 
Cavallo harshly reacted to the pressure being exerted by 
Washington for the approval of this controversial draft bill. 
  Cavallo said: "Since it is so important to them, let us use 
the patents law as a negotiating tool to obtain better terms for 
our exports." 
  Among other things, the current patents law allows 
pharmaceutical laboratories to freely use formulas that do not 
belong to them, which has generated serious criticism and 
pressure by the U.S. Government. 
  For more than a year now the official intellectual property 
draft bill has been blocked in Congress by government and 
opposition legislators who are against it. 
  This is not the first time Cavallo has voiced doubts about 
the simple approval of the draft bill. What is more, during a 
recent economic team meeting, Cavallo and Economic Programming 
Secretary Juan Jose Llach agreed on the disproportionate U.S. 
interest in the draft bill's approval and what they are willing 
to grant in exchange. 
  Cavallo now has asserted: "We will approve the patents law 
when we, in exchange, can join NAFTA or obtain greater 
facilities for the entry of our exports." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-10509 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat071_k_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
