<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dejoie Criticizes Aristide in Published Letter </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dejoie Criticizes Aristide in Published Letter </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL1304210394 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1030 
GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1304210394 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Priest-President Jean-Bertrand Aristide is not 
qualified to fill the high office of president of the Republic 
of Haiti, according to Louis Dejoie II, acting minister of 
commerce and industry, advancing the opinion that the latest 
communique on the Port Tortuga matter has demonstrated the 
meanness of the president and his lack of political maturity and 
ability to analyze state affairs. In a letter to the general 
director of the weekly HAITI EN MARCHE, Dejoie assails the 
president as audacious. He writes: It seems odd that I can be 
accused of being a traitor -- unless this accusation comes from 
a mentally ill, malicious, racist, and embittered Haitian 
jealous of my democratic stands in favor of the Haitian people. 
  Louis Dejoie II explains that he is not seeking revenge and 
has not raised a destructive weapon against Haitian brothers, 
political clans, or social strata but has always preached 
national reconciliation. Dejoie says he is the victim of a plot 
against him hatched by the lavalasians. A lavalas brigade from 
Miami is allegedly already in Port-au-Prince for the purpose of 
assassinating Minister Dejoie. That would be something! he 
exclaims, in this letter to the general director of HAITI EN 
MARCHE. 

</TEXT>

