<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Salinas on Article 27, Ejido Privatization </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Salinas on Article 27, Ejido Privatization </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1304194094 Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1304194094 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=105> Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jaime Guerrero; from the "Early Morning" </F>
newscast; passages within quotation marks are recorded] 
  [Text] President Salinas said that reforms to Article 27 of 
the Constitution do not mean the privatization of the Mexican 
countryside. Issuing property titles for the peasants' land is 
an act of justice, not an act of alienation. He also said that 
ejidos will not be privatized. 
  [Salinas] "These titles mean justice, not alienation." 
  He pointed out that two years after Article 27 was amended, 
only 38 of the 30,000 Mexican ejidos have requested the full 
issuance of property titles to become part of the real estate 
market. 
  [Salinas] "Urban areas are already surrounding those 38 
ejidos. Without property titles, their prospects, as Agrarian 
Prosecutor Arturo Warman already said, would include only 
expropriation or, even worse, invasion and loss of their own 
legacy." 
  Salinas pointed out there currently is a sound possibility 
of 
overcoming poverty and neglect in the countryside. In short, 
the validity of Article 27 was discussed. 
  [Warman] "We did not find any reason to revise Article 27 of 
the Constitution." 
  Prosecutor Warman said that a reform to Article 27 would 
constitute a setback; in addition, the reform lacks the support 
of the majority of peasants. He added that only minority groups 
are requesting modifications to the article. He also talked 
about Chiapas and rejected that legal large estates are 
predominantly in the hands of a few individuals. 
  [Warman] "We will continue to search for legal large 
estates, 
but I believe that we will find very few." 
  Warman submitted to the president his second report on the 
works of the Agrarian Prosecutor's Office. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

