<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Sends Protest Letter to U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Sends Protest Letter to U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1304193694 Panama City Telemetro Television Network in 
Spanish 1730 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1304193694 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City Telemetro Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Telemetro Reports" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The Panamanian Government has issued a formal 
protest to the U.S. Government over recent statements that 
Panama is not cooperating enough in the struggle against drug 
trafficking and money laundering. 
  Jose Raul Mulino sent a four-page letter noting that the 
U.S. 
statements are general and subjective. He added that the 
Panamanian Government has taken many actions to fight those 
crimes. 
  In the document, Mulino says that Panama is not an economic 
power and on many occasions it has had to establish it 
priorities. Regarding the struggle against drug trafficking, our 
cooperation has been expeditious and in good faith. 
  Mulino asked for a meeting at the highest level, with the 
participation of the financial sector, to discuss this problem. 
  The letter clearly states that the national government has 
not eluded its responsibility. 

</TEXT>

