<F P=100> Honduras </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1204223294 </F>
<F P=103> PA1204223294 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Honduran economic developments reported through 12 
April. 
  Tegucigalpa Telesistema Hondureno de Television in Spanish 
0100 GMT 6 Apr 94 reports the government confirmed on 6 April 
that fuel prices will be adjusted every 15 days. A government 
official said that fuel prices will be based on an average of 
international prices and that the government will prevent 
profiteering. It was officially announced on 6 April that 
electricity rates will be increased for those who consume 300 kw 
of electricity or more. 
  Panama City ACAN in Spanish 2141 GMT 11 Apr 94 reports that 
according to a study conducted by the Honduran Economists 
Association, food prices increased 21 percent in the first three 
months of Carlos Reina's administration. Reina's economic 
cabinet eliminated $8 million worth of fuel subsidies and 
increased the dollar exchange rate from 6.20 to 7.27 lempiras in 
March. The Honduran Central Bank revealed that the consumer 
price index increased 1 percent, compared with 0.2-percent 
increase in March 1993. Martin Barahona, vice president of the 
Economists Association, said that 1.5 million people are able to 
work but 25 percent of them are unemployed or underemployed. 
Barahona added that eight out of 10 Hondurans live below the 
poverty level. 

</TEXT>

