<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Venezuela's Sosa Says Free Trade Talks Stalled </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Venezuela's Sosa Says Free Trade Talks Stalled </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1404180594 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1500 GMT 13 Apr 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1404180594 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Ren Avila] </F>
  [Text] Guadalajara, 13 Apr (NOTIMEX) -- The free trade 
agreement that Mexico, Colombia, and Venezuela are negotiating 
is at a stalemate over Venezuela's disagreement with Mexico on 
the matter of asymmetry, rules of origin, and government 
purchases. 
  Venezuelan Finance Minister Julio Sosa Rodriguez said here 
in 
this western Mexican city that nevertheless, his country is 
fully confident the pact will be finalized in the next months. 
Interviewed within the framework of the 35th annual meeting of 
the Assembly of Governors of the Inter-American Development Bank 
(IDB), the Venezuelan official said that his country wants a 
total commercial opening. 
  He explained that the diversification of markets should be 
done in a just, equitable fashion so the three economies can 
reap equal benefits from the trade pact without any one country 
taking undue advantages. 
  "The southern part of the continent already has a common 
market. This accord with Mexico and Colombia is meant to 
establish a mechanism for opening with commercial exchanges that 
reflect guarantees as if we were a single country," he indicated. 
  Sosa says Mexico must recognize that Venezuelan products are 
at a disadvantage in the areas of basic industry and capital 
goods. 
  Sosa Rodriguez declined to comment on the obstacles that 
exist regarding the rules of origin and government purchases, 
although he said that no progress has been made on those topics 
because the negotiations have been delayed. 
  Sosa said that his country's oil will not be a subject for 
negotiation in the free trade pact since Mexico is not willing 
to do the same. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

