<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radical Party, Labor Agree To Push Reforms </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Radical Party, Labor Agree To Push Reforms </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1404221694 Buenos Aires BUENOS AIRES HERALD in English 14 
Apr 94 p 13 </F>

<F P=103> PY1404221694 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires BUENOS AIRES HERALD </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] (NA-DYN) -- The General Labour Confederation 
(CGT) and the Radical Party agreed yesterday [13 April] to push 
reforms to the Labour bill promoted by the government and to 
seek the support of the Church for this purpose. 
  Trade union leaders did not specify the points discussed but 
said both sides had opposed the planned overhaul of the 
union-run health insurance system. 
  ANSSAL [National Health Insurance Administration] national 
health administration director Jose Luis Lingiero unveiled an 
alternative union-backed health insurance scheme which advocates 
a gradual deregulation of the current system. The proposal will 
be presented to the government and businessmen. 
  The proposal came as a direct reply to Economy Minister 
Domingo Cavallo, who criticized the social welfare funds during 
a visit to Mexico, branding the Argentine system as corrupt. 
  "The union medical plans are and always will be a guarantee 
of health for workers, often replacing the inefficient public 
health system," Cassia said in a communique aired after his 
meeting with Alfonsin. 
  "One thing is to change for the better and another to 
pretend 
to overcome alleged shortcomings by handing health services over 
to other sectors which privilege profits over workers' needs," 
he added. 
  Cassia also told reporters the Radical Party had agreed to 
negotiate all future labour-related draft laws with CGT. 
  Also yesterday Alfonsin and the CGT chief ratified their 
wish 
to curtail the president's power to sign emergency decrees and 
analyzed the make-up of the future Socio-Economic Council to be 
set up after the reform of the Constitution. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

