<H3> <TI>   Menem, Alfonsin Reaffirm Olivos Pact </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Menem, Alfonsin Reaffirm Olivos Pact </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1404221594 Buenos Aires BUENOS AIRES HERALD in English 14 
Apr 94 p 13 </F>

<F P=103> PY1404221594 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires BUENOS AIRES HERALD </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] (DYN-NA) -- Both signatories of the Olivos Pact 
on constitutional reform, President Carlos Menem and Radical 
Party chairman Raul Alfonsin, moved yesterday [13 April] to 
squelch continuing rumours that the accord would be opened up 
for point-by-point negotiations yesterday. 
  The Radical leader also continued to defend his decision to 
support the ruling Justicialist Party's reform platform last 
year despite his party's distant second-place finish in Sunday's 
[10 April] Constituent Assembly election. 
  "I have complete assurance," Menem said yesterday, "that no 
matter how much (Radical Deputy) Jesus Rodriguez has expressed 
his desire to support Frente (Grande) or make an alliance" the 
pact will be fulfilled. 
  Rodriguez led the Radicals' Federal Capital slate of 
candidates to a third-place finish in a district that until last 
year's congressional election had been the party's stronghold. 
Following Sunday's election he raised the possibility of forming 
a broad opposition coalition to defeat Menem next year if the 
Constituent Assembly approves the Olivos Pact, which would 
permit the President to run for two consecutive terms in office. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

